	<text>
		<body>
			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB0651_01.jpg"/> The person in question has given us the following information: In <date when="1941"
					>1941</date>, I lived in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/688365/yasinya.html">Kőrösmező</placeName>, my <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">parents</term> owned land, and even two houses, I had
				three brothers and sisters. My father was taken into Poland <note type="gloss">The testimony is not precise. The survivor was taken to
					the occupied zone of the former Ukraine</note>, later they also took me, my older brother, and my older sister. They left me on a
				cornfield, from where I managed to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escape</term> and
				came back to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/688365/yasinya.html">Kőrösmező</placeName> crossing the <placeName
					ref="https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q131210">Dnyeszter</placeName>. I went into <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hiding</term> for nine months on the attic. Once an
					<term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_ukrainians">Ukrainian</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">woman</term> noticed how much my sister cooked and
				baked and got suspicious. In the meantime my mother <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject"
					>died</term> and as it started to be very dangerous staying on the attic we came to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054643/budapest.html">Budapest</placeName>. As far as I know, it was a <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_hungarians">Hungarian</term> shoemaker who <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-195" type="subject">denounced</term> us claiming that someone was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hiding</term> on the attic. <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1125" type="subject">Gendarmes</term> searched the house. Here, in
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054643/budapest.html">Budapest</placeName> the <orgName
					ref="#ehri_et_jewish_supportive_office_in_budapest">Jewish Supportive Office</orgName> put me into an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-327" type="subject">orphanage</term> where I stayed for two years, when I
				was summoned for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-560" type="subject">labourservice</term> in <date
					when="1944-06">June of 1944</date>. I got to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054663/budafok.html">Budafok</placeName>
				where they <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655" type="subject">took</term> all my belongings, my watch,
				and my money. There was a <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_hungarians">Hungarian</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">warrant officer</term> who beat us up terribly. He
				made the people from the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-327" type="subject">orphanage</term> standing
				aside and he meant to send us home, but later changed his mind. From here we got to the brick factory of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054651/budakalasz.html">Budakalász</placeName> and with the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> for the people from the agglomeration of
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054643/budapest.html">Pest</placeName> we were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">entrained</term> 74 of us in a car. We got water at
				departure and were escorted by <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_hungarians">Hungarian</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1125" type="subject">gendarmes</term> till <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/724443/kosice.html">Kassa</placeName> where the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">train</term> was handed over to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">Germans</term>, who gave no water but shot into to
				the freight cars all the time. The <date when="1944-07-03">3rd of July</date>, at 10 am we arrived in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Auschwitz</placeName>, where <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">prisoners</term> in striped <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">clothes</term> were waiting for us. We had to leave
				our luggage in the cars, and to queue up <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term>
				and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> separately. I was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">selected</term> for the group for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>, and was taken into a baths where they cut
				my hair off and gave me striped <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836">clothes</term>. We
				were put into a barrack where they ordered us to present all our valuables because they claimed they had a machine that could see
				through us and if they found anything on you, you were going to be <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541">hanged</term>. We got into <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Camp A</placeName>, where there were around 600 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> in a block. I saw the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501" type="subject">crematorium</term> and often felt the smell of burnt
				bones but they told us they were burning old <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject"
					>clothes</term>. Every day twice there was a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject"
					>roll call</term> that lasted for hours; <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
					>food</term> was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">scarce</term>. <pb n="2"
					facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB0651_02.jpg"/> After a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject"
					>selection</term> I was sent to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-43">Buchenwald</placeName>. The
				journey was around four days long, we were 50 of us in a freight car, they gave us nothing to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">eat</term> although there was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> in the car but they kept it, so we had to
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">starve</term> all the way. When we arrived we
				had a bath and received a loaf of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread,
					margarine</term>, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">jam</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">sausage</term>. They put us up in the tent <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term> which was a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">concentration camp</term>, and they sent us from here
				to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2849266/rehmsdorf.html">Remmsdorf</placeName> for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>. The journey lasted again three days, we
				were 50 of us again in a car and received two third of a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
					type="subject">loaf</term>, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">margarine</term> and
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">jam</term>. The day after that we arrived, I was
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">selected</term> for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> in a petrol company called <orgName
					ref="#ehri_et_brabag">Brabach</orgName> where I <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject"
					>worked</term> 12 hours a day. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">lager</term>
				lay approximately 2 kilometres away from the plant. 650 of us stayed in a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">barrack</term>, two in a bed. <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_hungarians">Hungarian</term> speaking <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS men</term> guarded us in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term>, and often beat us up. If they simply did
				not like someone they made him get out of line and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject"
					>killed</term> him. I saw once that they <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject"
					>killed</term> someone with a blow in the outlying <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-489"
					type="subject">kommando</term>. Every day in the winter there were 40-50 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-515" type="subject">dead bodies</term>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">scarce</term> and it was very cold. <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">Death</term> found a fertile soil here. Before
				Christmas, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1078" type="subject">Americans</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1105" type="subject">bombed</term> the plant but lowered yellow lamps
				from the aircrafts to indicate the place of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject"
					>lager</term>, as a result, no one got hurt. For a while I served a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-485" type="subject">Capo</term> as his servant. <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2849266/rehmsdorf.html">Remmsdorf</placeName> is next to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2879139/leipzig.html">Leipzig</placeName>. Later, our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">lager</term> started to clear debris, that was what I
				did, too. We got <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> in the houses but we
				also stole when we could not get hold of it otherwise. At the end of March, <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_americans">American</term> troops were only 3-4 kilometres away. That night at 1 am they quickly
				entrained us and we started off in the direction of <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449"
					>Theresienstadt</placeName>. We came till Tarienburg by <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518"
					type="subject">train</term> when low-flying airplanes <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1105"
					type="subject">bombed</term> two of our railway engines. We had 350 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">sick</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term>. Those who were not <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">sick</term> tried to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">ran away</term>; we went to the village, and by the
				time we came back we saw that <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-515" type="subject">dead</term> bodies
				were being carrying: three cars were full of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-515" type="subject"
					>dead</term> bodies. We asked what had happened and were informed that the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName> had <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term> those unfortunate. At this point we
				started <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-517" type="subject">walking</term>. Those who could not keep
				pace and sat down at the sides of the road were cruelly shot by the guards. When we started our journey we were in 3,800 in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term>, when we arrived to <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449">Theresienstadt</placeName>, there were only 800 of us alive, but
				around the half <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-493" type="subject">typhus</term> in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449">Theresienstadt</placeName>. The <date when="1945-05-09">9th of
					May</date>, the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583">Red Army</orgName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">liberated</term> us in the town. I stayed three
				weeks in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449">Theresienstadt</placeName> before we left for
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> already in a bigger group. In <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> I spent three weeks at the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-419">Red Cross</orgName>, where we were disinfected and provided with
				everything good. I came home through <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> and <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3060972/bratislava.html">Pozsony</placeName>. My future plan: I return to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-327" type="subject">orphanage</term>.</p>
